Are there any plans to move forward with this? We currently have the following setup in `appsettings.Development.json` in our local development:

```json
  "Authentication": {
    "Schemes": {
      "TokenScheme": {
        "ValidAudiences": [
          "dummy-audience"
        ],
        "ValidIssuer": "https://localhost:7000",
        "Authority": "https://localhost:7000"
      }
    }
  }
```

This allows us to either use tokens from an authorization server running at `localhost:7000` or the tokens generated by `dotnet user-jwts`. But if we run `dotnet user-jwts create --issuer "https://localhost:7000" --audience "dummy-audience" --scheme "TokenScheme" --project project-path-goes-here` the `Authority` field in appsettings gets removed, and the appsettings file looks like this instead:

```json
  "Authentication": {
    "Schemes": {
      "TokenScheme": {
        "ValidAudiences": [
          "dummy-audience"
        ],
        "ValidIssuer": "https://localhost:7000"
      }
    }
  }
```

Without the `Authority` field we cannot use the local authorization server. We would like to either prevent `dotnet user-jwts` from modifying `appsettings.Development.json` or also pass the `Authority` setting to `dotnet user-jwts`. I do understand that the `Authority` setting does not have any bearing on tokens generated by the command though.

